":"1149","1148":"1148","1214":"1214","1203":"1203","1257":"1257","1135":"1135","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1243":"1243","Albert, Somme, Picardie, France":"Albert, Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1148–1214":"1148–1214","1145–1198":"1145–1198","1149–1200":"1149–1200","1152–1203":"1152–1203","1179–1243":"1179–1243","1198–1257":"1198–1257","1098–1161":"1098–1161","1105–1145":"1105–1145","1198":"1198","1098":"1098","1196":"1196","1152":"1152","1161":"1161","1105":"1105","1149":"1149","1148":"1148","1214":"1214","1203":"1203","1257":"1257","1135":"1135","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1243":"1243","Albert, Somme, Picardie, France":"Albert, Somme, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"D'Encre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Herta.","English (Kent): variant of <b>Dench</b>, an ethnic name for someone from Denmark, from Middle English <i>denshe</i>, <i>dench</i> ‘Danish’ (Old English <i>denisc</i>). There were many Danes in England in the Middle Ages, not only the long-established settlers in the Danelaw region, but also more recent immigrants."],"variants":[{"name":"Denmark","meanings":["English (Norfolk): ethnic name denoting someone from Denmark (see   Dence  ). In the British Isles this name is found mainly in East Anglia.","Americanized form of German <b>Dennemark</b>, ethnic name for someone from Denmark, from Middle Low German <i>Dennemarken</i>."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Clermont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jacques, Georges, Normand, Pierre, Armand, Edouard, Gaston, Ghislaine, Gilles, Henri, Herve, Jean Francois.","French and English (Middlesex, of Norman and French Huguenot origin): habitational name from any of various places in France called (Le) Clermont, from Old French <i>clair</i>, <i>cler</i> ‘bright, clear’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’, i.e. a hill that could be seen a long way off. Compare   Clairmont  .","English (Middlesex, of Norman and possibly also Huguenot origin): variant of <b>Claremont</b>, from the Old French female personal name <i>Claremonde</i>, supposedly from ancient Germanic <i>Claremunda</i>, a hybrid compound of Latin <i>clarus</i> ‘famous’ + ancient Germanic <i>mund</i> ‘protection’."],"variants":[{"name":"Clairmont","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adelard, Aime, Antoine, Aurore, Fernand.","French: variant of   Clermont   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this. The surname <i>Clairmont</i> is very rare in France.","In some cases possibly also English: variant of <b>Claremont</b> or   Clermont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Gaucher","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Armand, Francoise, Jacques, Laurette, Lucien, Philippe.","French:","from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Walhari</i>, composed of the elements <i>walh</i> ‘stranger’ and <i>hari</i> ‘army’."],"variants":[{"name":"Coetzee","meanings":["Afrikaans: probably an altered form of Dutch <b>Goetzee</b>, which is of French Huguenot origin, probably from   Gaucher  . Alternatively, <i>Coetzee</i> may be an altered form of Dutch <b>Kuzee</b>, a habitational name recorded in the 16th century as <i>Cudsee</i> and <i>Cutsee</i>, from a toponym located in Zeeland, which may be interpreted as <i>Cut's-see</i> ‘watercourse of Cudo’.","History: Dirk Coetzee, born in Kampen in the Netherlands around 1655, died in Cape Town in 1725."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gaucher D'Encre de Clermont was born in 1148, in Albert, Somme, Picardie, France, his father, Baudouin d'Encre, was 50 and his mother, Marguerite de Clermont en Beauvaisis, was 43. He married Alexandrine de Caulaincourt in 1196. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1214, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1148–1214":"1148–1214","1145–1198":"1145–1198","1149–1200":"1149–1200","1152–1203":"1152–1203","1179–1243":"1179–1243","1198–1257":"1198–1257","1098–1161":"1098–1161","1105–1145":"1105–1145","1198":"1198","1098":"1098","1196":"1196","1152":"1152","1161":"1161","1105":"1105","1149":"1149","1148":"1148","1214":"1214","1203":"1203","1257":"1257","1135":"1135","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1243":"1243","Albert, Somme, Picardie, France":"Albert, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1148–1214":"1148–1214","1145–1198":"1145–1198","1149–1200":"1149–1200","1152–1203":"1152–1203","1179–1243":"1179–1243","1198–1257":"1198–1257","1098–1161":"1098–1161","1105–1145":"1105–1145","1198":"1198","1098":"1098","1196":"1196","1152":"1152","1161":"1161","1105":"1105","1149":"1149","1148":"1148","1214":"1214","1203":"1203","1257":"1257","1135":"1135","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1243":"1243","Albert, Somme, Picardie, France":"Albert, Somme, Picardie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1148–1214":"1148–1214","1145–1198":"1145–1198","1149–1200":"1149–1200","1152–1203":"1152–1203","1179–1243":"1179–1243","1198–1257":"1198–1257","1098–1161":"1098–1161","1105–1145":"1105–1145","1198":"1198","1098":"1098","1196":"1196","1152":"1152","1161":"1161","1105":"1105","1149"